The '''A671''' is a road in the [[North West England|North West]] of [[England]], that runs between [[Oldham]], [[Greater Manchester]] and [[Worston]], near [[Clitheroe]], [[Lancashire]]. Major towns on the route include [[Rochdale]] and [[Burnley]]. The road is approximately {{convert|35|mi|km}} long. Between Burnley and the [[A59 road|A59]], the A671 has [[primary road|primary]] status.

The section of road between Burnley and [[Whalley, Lancashire|Whalley]] has been identified as one of the [[United Kingdom|UK]]'s ten most dangerous roads, with 48 serious or fatal collisions between 2000-2005.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6236636.stm | title=Britain's most dangerous roads | publisher=[[BBC News]] | date=2007-06-25 | accessdate=2008-03-09 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080229074117/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6236636.stm| archivedate= 29 February 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

==Route==
The southern end of the road, formerly part of the [[A627 road|A627]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html#389,414,1 | title=New Popular Edition Maps | accessdate=2008-03-09 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080314030500/http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html| archivedate= 14 March 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> was the main route from Oldham to Rochdale until it was bypassed by the [[A627(M) motorway]] in 1972.
Between Rochdale and [[Bacup]], the road passes through the small town of [[Whitworth, Lancashire|Whitworth]]. The {{convert|3|mi|adj=on}} section through the town is called Market Street, and has several speed cameras as well as being the scene of a number of accidents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.lancashireeveningtelegraph.co.uk/2008/3/7/1082612.html |title=Crisis talks over 'danger' road |date=2008-03-07 |accessdate=2008-03-08 |work=[[Lancashire Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Newsquest Media Group]] }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

The road passes through the centre of [[Bacup]], where it crosses the [[A681 road|A681]]. It then processes through [[Broadclough]] and [[Weir]] before going over Deerplay Moor. It later crosses the [[A646 road|A646]] before reaching [[Burnley]]. North of Burnley the A671 is a [[primary road]]. There is a junction with the [[M65 motorway]] (junction 10) before the road passes through [[Padiham]], a small town within the borough of Burnley. The A671 forms the [[High Street|main street]] through the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clitheroethefuture.co.uk/market_town_report_padiham.html |title=Padiham Case Study |publisher=Clitheroe the Future |year=2008 |accessdate=2008-03-09 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514193600/http://www.clitheroethefuture.co.uk/market_town_report_padiham.html |archivedate=14 May 2008 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref> Beyond Padiham is a stretch of the road known as the Devils Elbow, near the village of [[Read, Lancashire|Read]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www3.lancashire.gov.uk/corporate/news/press_releases/2004/06/22/0003.asp | title=News: Works On A671 Whalley Road, Read | publisher=Lancashire County Council | date=2004-06-22 | accessdate=2008-03-09 }}</ref> Further to the north-west there is the junction with the [[A680 road|A680]].

The road then bypasses Whalley, and ends at a roundabout, joining the [[A59 road|A59]] near [[Barrow, Clitheroe|Barrow]]. {{convert|2|mi}} further north-east, the road leaves the A59. This section of the A671 is non-primary and forms a loop through the town of Clitheroe, which is bypassed by the A59 to the south and east of the town. It heads to the north through Clitheroe, and heads east as it leaves the town, terminating at another junction with the A59 again near [[Worston]].

==Bypass Proposals==

There have been a large number of road traffic incidents on the A671 as it passes through the small hamlets of [[Broadclough]] and [[Weir, Lancashire|Weir]] near [[Bacup]] including fatalities. Currently police are monitoring the road<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/northwest/11308062.Police_monitoring_Bacup_Weir_accident__blackspot_/ | title=Police Monitoring Bacup Weir Accident Blackspot | work=[[The Bolton News]] | publisher=[[The Bolton News]]}}</ref> and there have been calls from local residents, led by County Councillor Jimmy Easton,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/northwest/11172039.UPDATED__Man_fighting_for_life_after_Bacup_crash/ | title=UPDATED: Man fighting for life after Bacup crash | publisher= Bolton News}}</ref> for the creation of a bypass with the suggestion of utilising elements of the old highway Bacup Old Road.

