{{for|the [[Romania]]n commune called Kékes in Hungarian|Chiochiș}} {{Infobox mountain | name = Kékes | photo = Kékestető.JPG | photo_caption = | photo_size = 250 | elevation_m = 1014 | elevation_ref = <ref name=pb>{{cite pb|name=Kékes|id=10314}}</ref> | prominence_m = 774 | prominence_ref = <ref name=pb/> | map = Hungary | map_caption = Hungary | map_size = 250 | label_position = left | listing = [[List of countries by highest point|Country high point]] | translation = Bluish | language = [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] | location = [[Heves (county)|Heves county]], [[Hungary]] | range = [[Mátra]], [[Western Carpathians]] | coordinates = {{coord|47|52|44|N|20|0|37|E|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | topo = | type = | age = | first_ascent = | easiest_route = }}
'''Kékes''' {{IPA-hu|ˈkeːkɛʃ|}} is [[Hungary]]'s [[List of elevation extremes by country|highest]] [[mountain]], at {{convert|1015|m|}} above sea level.<ref name=pb/> It lies {{convert|12|km}} northeast of [[Gyöngyös]],<ref name="Földvary">{{cite book |author=G. Z. Földvary |year=1988 |title=Geology of the Carpathian Region |publisher=World Scientific |isbn=978-9971-5-0345-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B7dNVzg4UHIC&pg=PA278}}</ref> in the [[Mátra]] range of [[Heves County|Heves county]]. It is Hungary's third most popular [[tourist attraction]], after [[Lake Balaton]] and the [[Danube]], and has a number of hotels and skiing [[piste]]s. The [[Kékestető TV Tower]] stands at the summit.
The name ''Kékes'' is derived from the mountain's often bluish colour. In [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], the word ''{{lang|hu|kék}}'' means 'blue', while ''{{lang|hu|kékes}}'' means implicitly 'bluish'.
==Road cycling== For [[road bicycle racing]] enthusiasts, the mountain can be climbed by two main routes.
* South from [[Gyöngyös]]: 839 m over 17.8&nbsp;km. This is the most famous and difficult ascent. * North from [[Parád]]: 775 m over 16.9&nbsp;km. About equal in difficulty as the Bédoin ascent, but better sheltered against the climb.
