{{Infobox mountain | name = Mount Obama | other_name = ''Boggy Peak'' | photo = Boggy Peak.JPG | photo_caption = Mount Obama | elevation_m = 402 | elevation_ref = <ref>[http://www.summitpost.org/mount-obama-once-boggy-peak/327589 "Mount Obama" on summitpost.org] Retrieved 2011-09-29.</ref> | prominence_m = 402 | prominence_ref = <ref name="pb"/> | map = Antigua and Barbuda | map_alt = | map_caption = | label_position = | listing = [[List of countries by highest point|Country high point]] | location = [[Antigua and Barbuda]] | range = | coordinates = {{coord|17|02|31|N|61|51|04|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = <ref name="pb">[http://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=8255 "Mount Obama" on Peakbagger] Retrieved 2011-09-29.</ref> | topo = | type = | age = | first_ascent = | easiest_route = }}
'''Mount Obama''' (known as '''Boggy Peak''' until August 4, 2009) is the highest point of the [[Shekerley Mountains]] and of the island of [[Antigua]]. It lies in the southwest of the island at {{coord|17|2|31|N|61|51|4|W}},<ref name="pb"/><ref>{{cite web |title=NGA GEOnet Names Server |publisher=[[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]] |date=2008-07-07 |url=http://www.nima.mil/gns/html/index.html |accessdate=2008-07-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031008130923/http://www.nima.mil/gns/html/index.html |archivedate=2003-10-08 |df= }}</ref> and rises to a height of {{convert|402|m|ft|0}} and is named after [[Barack Obama]], the 44th [[President of the United States]].
==Renaming== On August 4, 2009, the 48th birthday of U.S. President [[Barack Obama]], [[Antigua and Barbuda|Antiguan]] Prime Minister [[Baldwin Spencer]] renamed the mountain Mount Obama. Its former name was Boggy Peak.<ref name=ap>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/08/04/mount-obama-antigua-renam_n_251173.html| title=Mount Obama: Antigua Renames Its Highest Peak| last=Kentish| first=Anika| publisher=Huffington Post| agency=Associated Press| accessdate=2011-03-09| date=2009-08-09}}</ref>
